      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is a commercially validated FEA solver with documented V&V procedures. FDA in-house scripts are version-controlled in Git with unit-test coverage >85%. DePuy Synthes simulation environment operates under ISO 13485 QMS with periodic software qualification audits. Achieved level 3 reflects formal QMS coverage across all three modeling environments."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Benchmark problems from the ASME V&V 10.1 suite (cantilever beam, Hertzian contact) were executed in each modeling environment and results compared to analytical solutions. Maximum deviation was 0.8%, confirming correct implementation of governing equations. Achieved level 2 reflects successful completion of standard verification benchmarks."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study performed across three refinement levels (coarse ~120k elements, medium ~380k elements, fine ~950k elements). Richardson extrapolation applied to stiffness and peak force QoIs; GCI values ranged from 0.4% to 1.1%, all below the 2% threshold. Final production mesh uses medium density with local refinement at screw-rod interface. Achieved level 3 reflects quantified discretization uncertainty with GCI < 2%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error was identified as beyond the scope of the current credibility package. The assessment team noted that solver residuals and iterative convergence tolerances were set to Ansys defaults, and that a formal evaluation of solver-induced error contributions was not conducted within the project timeline. This factor is deferred to a future revision of the credibility evidence package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment was considered outside the scope of the current submission. The simulation workflow is operated by experienced analysts and informal peer review is practiced, but no structured use-error analysis (e.g., FMEA on analyst actions, documented operator qualification records) was performed. The team acknowledged this gap but judged it beyond the immediate submission scope without providing quantitative justification for the omission at model risk level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic material model applied to titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) implant components; UHMWPE vertebral body surrogates modeled with bilinear isotropic hardening calibrated from coupon testing. Contact between screw and rod modeled with penalty-based frictional contact (mu=0.3). Model form selections are consistent with prior published FDA studies and supported by literature. Achieved level 3 reflects documented justification of all constitutive and contact modeling choices."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Material properties sourced from MMPDS-11 for Ti-6Al-4V and from coupon testing for UHMWPE surrogates (n=5 tensile specimens per lot). Geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of production implants (n=3). Torque preload on set screw measured with calibrated torque wrench and applied as prescribed displacement in FEA. Uncertainty in all primary inputs quantified and propagated. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens drawn from the same production lot; dimensional inspection confirmed compliance with drawing tolerances. Sample size supports detection of systematic bias at 80% power for the pre-specified 10% acceptance bound. Achieved level 2 reflects adequate but not exhaustive sample characterization."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level. NOTE: This factor is below required level — identified as a known gap in the validation evidence.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted under a single loading configuration (ASTM F1717 standard fixture, 10 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature). No variation in loading rate, temperature, or fixture alignment was explored. The single test condition limits the ability to assess model sensitivity to boundary condition variations. Achieved level 1 reflects testing at a single standardized condition only; this shortfall is documented and accepted given the regulatory precedent for F1717 as a standard method."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry as measured by CMM. Applied displacement rate in FEA matched to quasi-static assumption consistent with 10 mm/min experimental rate. Material properties used in simulation derived from the same production lot as test specimens. Correspondence between experimental and simulation input parameters formally documented in a parameter mapping table. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison performed for three QoIs: construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. Validation metric E/uval computed per ASME V&V 10-2019; all values below 1.96 threshold. Percentage differences: stiffness max 7.2%, yield force mean 4.3%, force at 40 mm mean 6.8% — all within the pre-specified 10% acceptance bound. Statistical equivalence confirmed. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the primary QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly linked to the clinical performance indicators for pedicle screw constructs (fatigue life surrogate, structural integrity under physiological loading). The mapping from simulation QoIs to device performance requirements is documented in the design verification plan. Achieved level 3 reflects explicit traceability from QoI to clinical risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Validation activity directly replicates the intended use scenario: the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry, the same loading mode (compression-bending), and the same regulatory test standard (ASTM F1717) as the COU. The validation is not an analogy to a similar device but a direct test of the specific device-model combination. Achieved level 2 reflects high but not exhaustive coverage of the COU parameter space (single loading condition)."
    }
  ],
